/*
FETCH
👉 Fetch is a built-in browser API (no installation needed) used to make HTTP requests.

Example==>>
fetch("https://api.example.com/data")
  .then((response) => response.json())
  .then((data) => console.log(data))
  .catch((error) => console.log(error));
  
  How Fetch Works
Returns a Promise
First .then() → gives Response object
You must manually convert:
response.json() → for JSON
response.text() → for text

👉 Fetch does NOT reject on HTTP errors like 404 or 500
❌ No built-in timeout

✅ Pros of Fetch
Built-in (no library needed)
Modern & widely supported
Works in browser + Node (with newer versions)
❌ Cons of Fetch
No automatic JSON parsing
No automatic error handling
No request timeout by default
Slightly more verbose

*/
/*
AXIOS
Axios is a third-party library used to make HTTP requests.
EXAMPLE ==>
    import axios from "axios";

axios.get("https://api.example.com/data")
  .then(res => console.log(res.data))
  .catch(err => console.log(err));

  👉 Axios automatically parses JSON
  ✅ Automatically throws error for bad status
Axios supports Interceptors
 axios.interceptors.request.use(config => {
  config.headers.Authorization = "Bearer token";
  return config;
});

👉 Used for:

Auth tokens
Logging
Global error handling

*/
/*
REST

REST is a way of designing APIs where resources are accessed using standard HTTP methods like GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE.




| Method | Purpose          | Example    |
| ------ | ---------------- | ---------- |
| GET    | Fetch data       | `/users`   |
| POST   | Create data      | `/users`   |
| PUT    | Update full data | `/users/1` |
| PATCH  | Update partial   | `/users/1` |
| DELETE | Remove data      | `/users/1` |

1. Client-Server Separation
Client (frontend) and server (backend) are separate
Frontend doesn’t care how backend works

2. Stateless
👉 Server does NOT store client state

Each request must contain all info

3. Cacheable
Responses can be cached
Improves performance

4. Uses standard HTTP

🔹Disadvantages

 Over-fetching (extra data)
 Under-fetching (multiple requests)
Multiple endpoints


GraphQL


“GraphQL is an API technology where the client specifies exactly what data it needs, and the server returns only that data.

🔹 Advantages

 Fetch only required data
 Single endpoint
 No versioning
 Strong typing
 Faster for complex app

🔹 Disadvantages

 Hard caching
 Heavy queries can slow server
 Needs setup (schema + resolvers)

 | Feature  | REST     | GraphQL  |
| -------- | -------- | -------- |
| Endpoint | Multiple | Single   |
| Data     | Fixed    | Flexible |
| Requests | Multiple | One      |
| Control  | Server   | Client   |

